, co-authored with Peter Colenbrander, which provides an extensive overview of the treaty process from 2001 to 2009. The authors outline the achievements of and challenges for the treaty process and review some of the most recent jurisprudence affecting Native and non-Native rights. They also reflect on the growing number of initiatives outside the treaty process to achieve reconciliation between First Nations and the Crown and raise questions about the future relationship between these initiatives and treaty negotiations. Treaty Talks in British Columbia is a valuable resource for those interested in Aboriginal issues and the treaty process both in BC and throughout Canada. Succinct, informative, and easy to read, this book brings clarity to a complex and often contentious issue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndian land transferszBritish Columbia. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLand tenurezBritish Columbia. 0aIndians of North AmericazBritish ColumbiaxClaims. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxTreaties. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Colonialism & Post-Colonialism.2bisacsh1 aColenbrander, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKee, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKee, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481516140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774815161423Coveruhttps://www.de